<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-083-097 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 143 747</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 12 1991 v25 n32 p61(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The sociology of software measurement. (includes related articleson necessary software measurement skills and how to organize ameasurement group)(In Depth)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jones, Capers.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Corporations implementing software measurement programs need to besensitive to social and corporate issues.andP;  It is essential thattop-level executives initiate such programs so that themeasurement policies are not seen by lower-level managers andtechnicians as having punitive purposes.andP;  Initial reactions tosoftware measurement programs usually are characterized byapprehension or opposition, but well-designed programs suffer thisresistance for only a month or so.andP;  Once workers are made awarethat results of software measurement programs will be used forpositive purposes, the programs are accepted and accuratemeasurement figures can be achieved.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software MetricsMeasurementManagement StyleEmployee RelationsProject Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>